TFG — Statistical Analysis

Methodology

The following questionnaires have been applied to the participating students:

  • RNPQ (Reliability and Pain Knowledge Questionnaire). Questionnaire with 12 questions with three possible answers (True, False, Undecided). 1 point is scored for each correct answer and 0 points for each incorrect answer or “Undecided”. The total score ranges from 0 to 12 points, with higher scores indicating greater knowledge about pain.

  • HC-PAIRS (Health care providers’ attitudes and beliefs about functional impairments and chronic back pain). Questionnaire with 15 questions with 7 possible answers on a Likert scale (from Totally Disagree to Totally Agree). It is scored from 1 to 7 points. The total score ranges from 15 to 105, with lower scores indicating more helpful pain attitudes.

# Packages loading.
library(tidyverse)
library(knitr)
library(broom)
library(vtable)
library(tidymodels)
library(ggpubr)
library(car)
library(rstatix)
# Data loading.
df <- read_csv("datos/datos-2024-04-22.csv") |>
    # Select the variables of interest.
    select(Degree, Course, Gender, RNPQ, HC_PAIRS, starts_with("X"), starts_with("Y")) |> 
    # Convert the categorical variables to factors.
    mutate(Degree = factor(Degree), Course = factor(Course), Gender = factor(Gender)) |> 
    # Create a new variable with the combination of the degree and the course.
    mutate(Degree_Course = interaction(Degree, Course))

The ANOVA test shows both, the degree and the course, have a statistically significant effect on the scores of the RNPQ questionnaire, and also the interaction between the degree and the course has a statistically significant effect (p-value < 0.05).

Caution

You should not trust the ANOVA results because the normality assumption is not met in some groups.

Mann-Whitney test

As the normality assumption is not met the courses, we will use the Mann-Whitney test to compare the scores of the RNPQ questionnaire between the couses.

wilcox.test(RNPQ ~ Course, data = df, alternative = "less") |> 
    tidy() |> 
    kable()
statistic p.value method alternative
11516 0 Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction less

The Mann-Whitney test shows a statistically significant difference between the first and the last course (p-value < 0.05).

Kruksal-Wallis test

As the normality assumption is not met in some groups, we will use the Kruksal-Wallis test to compare the scores of the RNPQ questionnaire among the Degree-Course groups .

kruskal.test(RNPQ ~ Degree_Course, data = df) |> 
    tidy() |> 
    kable()
statistic p.value parameter method
67.07969 0 7 Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

The Kruksal-Wallis test shows a statistically significant difference between the degrees (p-value < 0.05).

Two factors ANOVA for ranks

As the Kruskal-Wallis test can not be used for two factors, we can not study the interaction between the degree and the course. However, we can use the two factors ANOVA for ranks to study the effect of the degree and the course on the scores of the RNPQ questionnaire, and the interaction between the degree and the course.

anova_ranks <- aov(rank(RNPQ) ~ Degree * Course, data = df)
# Use the type III sum of squares as the groups are unbalanced.
Anova(anova_ranks, type = "III") |>
    tidy() |>
    kable()
term sumsq df statistic p.value
(Intercept) 258233.8 1 24.625322 0.0000010
Degree 163389.5 3 5.193638 0.0015827
Course 140892.6 1 13.435601 0.0002816
Degree:Course 246541.0 3 7.836763 0.0000434
Residuals 4026821.1 384 NA NA

The two factors ANOVA for ranks shows both, the degree and the course, have a statistically significant effect on the scores of the RNPQ questionnaire, and also the interaction between the degree and the course has a statistically significant effect (p-value < 0.05).
